":"1480–1513","1500–1607":"1500–1607","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1607":"1607","1480":"1480","Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England":"Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lancaster","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Lancaster in northwestern England, which is recorded as <i>Loncastre</i> in 1086. The place takes its name from the river Lune + Old English <i>ceaster</i> ‘city, Roman fortification’ (from Latin <i>castra</i> ‘legionary camp’). The river name is probably British, perhaps related to Gaelic <i>slán</i> ‘healthy’, ‘salubrious’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William Lancaster was born in 1480, in Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England. He had at least 1 son. He died in 1513, at the age of 33."},"et":{"1480–1513":"1480–1513","1500–1607":"1500–1607","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1607":"1607","1480":"1480","Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England":"Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England"},"fi":{"1480–1513":"1480–1513","1500–1607":"1500–1607","1513":"1513","1500":"1500","1607":"1607","1480":"1480","Sockbridge and Tirril, Westmorland, England":"Soc